ly gathers feminist scholars from diverse disciplines such as literature, women's studies, law, sociology, anthropology, creative writing, and critical theory and examines how Of Woman Born has informed and influenced the way feminist scholarship "thinks and talks" about motherhood. The contributors explore the many ways in which Rich provides the analytical tools to study and report upon the meaning and experience of motherhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 0aMotherhood in literature. 0aMotherhood. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAndrea O’Reilly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinn, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Fiona Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGullette, Margaret Morganroth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarman, Karin Voth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeremiah, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeniston, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuwabong, Dannabang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMccullough, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Reilly, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRandall, D’Arcy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiley, Jeannette E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, Sarah E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson-Franke, Maria-Barba